To further investigate the FL increase of UiO-66-NH2 caused by Pi, the transient FL spectra of the UiO-66-NH2 before and after the addition of ALP was compared (Fig. 3
                     ), and it turned out the obtained FL lifetime was almost the same (Table 1
                     ), which is the typical phenomenon for the static FL enhancement. Moreover, a broad absorption band around 320 nm was observed for UiO-66-NH2, where ALP or PP showed no UV absorption (Fig. 3). It was also found that this absorption was greatly enhanced with the addition of only Pi or the mixture of ALP and PP, but remained unchanged if ALP or PP was added separately (Fig. 3). It could thereby be concluded that the hydrolysis of PP by ALP was essential to the FL enhancement which could only be caused by the complexation between UiO-66-NH2 and Pi, the product of this hydrolysis, which was also defined as “absorbance caused enhancement (ACE) [38]. In this particular case, on one hand, the formation of UiO-66-NH2/Pi complexation would accordingly promote the excited state of UiO-66-NH2, so more energy is required for the transition from the ground to excited state; on the other hand, more energy in the FL form would be released after a series of vibration relaxation, leading to the enhanced FL emission derived from the formation of UiO-66-NH2/Pi complexation compared to the pristine UiO-66-NH2.

The correlation between the variation of FL intensity and the concentration of PP or UiO-66-NH2 NPs was investigated, and it was found out that 4 mM PP (Fig. 4
                     A) and 15 μg mL−1 UiO-66-NH2 NPs (Fig. 4B) were optimal. Under these conditions, the variation in FL intensity of UiO-66-NH2 NPs evolved with the ALP concentration up to 100 U L-1 was shown in Fig. 4 C, and it turned out that the linear range was 0.5–15 U L-1 (Fig. 4D), and an LOD, defined as the concentration equivalent to three times the standard deviation of 11 measurements of a blank solution, was 0.4 U L-1. Furthermore, this new technique was applied to the analysis of four serum samples collected from a local hospital. It turned out that the determined ALP levels were highly consistent with those by using the standard clinical procedures (Table 2
                     ), illustrating the promising perspective in the application of this technique for the proposed ALP assay in routine clinical assays of ALP in the future.
